Chapter 15: how's it feel
>Its the day of your first boxing match
>You're in a room waiting to be called out
>Jane is sitting with you rubbing your shoulders
>"You're going to do great out there babe," she purrs
>You were confident but still its your first match like this ever, so of course you were nervous

>You steel yourself and breathe in deep

>Jane has moved behind you and is massaging your shoulders
>"Time to glove up Titan"

>"Relax Babe"

>She kisses you softly and whispers "for good luck"

>"What did you expect Titan? A bull? A bear? The regulations say humans Vs humans at this level"
>You sigh and step into the ring

Not that dude, but that picture gave me a story idea, probably not going to do anything with it so maybe someone else might like it.

Imagine a hyper-advanced society, utterly post-scarcity and post-human. They zip around the galaxy in one-man ships - or occasionally grouping together for special occasions - doing whatever the fuck they want, paying little mind to consequences and simply rehosting themselves in new bodies when the last one gets old or too damaged to continue. They archive genetic material wherever they go, and design new outlandish and often impractical bodies simply because they can, referencing characteristics from a dozen different species to make an interesting form. The finer arts are practiced on a stellar scale, new celestial bodies being created simply to create a pleasing view for a few fleeting moments, and they often play elaborate games with lower life forms to entertain themselves.

One such game happens to a modern Earth. Humanity finds itself in a war with an unfathomable alien force, hounded on all sides by creatures that seemingly share no similarities to each other and have technologies so advanced as to be magic. Slowly, humanity is pushed to the edge of ruin, reduced to hundreds of loosely connected resistance groups, fighting dearly just to survive. Hope begins to shine for the first time for a resistance cell when they capture one of the aliens, though unusually without a fight.

The alien displays an interest in the primitive human species, and offers critical information and technology in return for the chance to study and experience their culture. She reveals that her people are hunting humanity for sport, intentionally handicapping themselves to give mankind a chance, and that there's no real reason other than boredom for their potential extinction.
